node.text: “At the end of my days, in my declining hours, I want to look in the mirror and see somebody who cared and tried to do all that he could to try to save nature as I know it and as I love it." Join Joel Sartore, National Geographic photographer, fellow, and founder of the Photo Ark, in celebrating the project's 15th anniversary. #photography #founder #nationalgeographic #project #savingwildlife #savingspecies #conservation #wildlife #PhotoArk #15YearsofPhotoArk

node.text: Sharing our gratitude for nature with one another is a small but meaningful way to honor and connect with our world and with each other. If we don’t savor nature while working to protect it, we risk losing sight of what we’re trying to save. I’m teaming up with @world_wildlife to invite you to share your love of nature with a photo or video that embodies that love. This week’s theme is wildlife, so here at the Photo Ark we are celebrating the diversity of aquatic species found around the globe. Share your appreciation for the natural world by using the hashtag #WhyILoveNature and tell us the story behind your post and @world_wildlife may re-post your share to their account! #ShowYourLoveForNature #photoark

node.text: Join me this evening at 10/9 pm central for the first installment of the two-hour Photo Ark special on NatGeo Wild. I’ll be diving deep underwater in the Amazon rainforest and soaring more than 12,000 feet above the tree line in the Colorado Rockies just to get the perfect shot, with a goal of inspiring people to care about all species before it’s too late. Tune in and let’s see what we can save together! #PhotoArkSpecial #PhotoArk #savetogether

node.text:
Today we’re crossing the 10,000 species mark with the güiña, a small wild cat photographed @fauna_andina in Chile! It’s been 15 years in the making, and we’ll keep going until we get every species in human care around the world - once the pandemic subsides, of course. Please join us in celebrating this milestone, and think about the ways that you can save species; reduce, reuse, recycle... but also insulate your home well, plant a pollinator garden, and never use chemicals of any kind on your lawn. You know the drill.
From all of us at Team Photo Ark, thank you. Now, let’s save them all! #PhotoArk #savetogether

node.text: Fourteen years ago, this project was created to try to get the world to care about the extinction crisis and inspire people around the globe to take action to save wildlife. A lot has changed since the project began - some species have seen their numbers rise for the first time in decades, many have been discovered and described by scientists for the first time, while others, sadly, have been lost forever. The world around us is constantly changing - a fact that is felt by each of us now more than ever as the current pandemic continues to alter our behaviors and the ways in which we interact with the world around us. We know things are tough right now, and it can be hard to feel like you’re making a difference in the world when you’re stuck in isolation, so today, we’re asking you to share both your challenges and successes when it comes to taking action to save wildlife in the comments section below. Throughout the year, we will continue to share tips and tricks on how you can save species from the comfort of your own home, and do our best to answer all of your saving-wildlife questions. Remember, no matter where you are, we are all in this together. #PhotoArk #savetogether #EarthDay

node.text: 15 Years of Photo Ark Celebration/ The Florida panther - the last big cat surviving in the eastern United States and the state animal of Florida, has the power to inspire the protection of millions of acres of wild Florida, save working lands, and keep the Everglades out of harm's way from sprawling development that is currently consuming more than 100,000 acres of wildlife habitat every year. Dedicated conservationists are hard at work protecting panthers like Lucy and the spaces they need to survive, but they need your help. Keep yourself informed and use your voice to advocate for wildlife so their stories do not fade from view. node.text: 15 Years of Photo Ark Celebration/ Wondering why these four-day-old mallard ducklings are fascinated with their reflections? No, it's not vanity - for these birds, the mirror creates the illusion of company. When the birds see their reflection, they believe they are seeing another bird, for species used to being in larger flocks, this mirror trick can be a tool to comfort birds and reduce any isolation-related stress they may be feeling. Video taken @intbirdrescue. #mallard #duck #ducklings #chicks #babies #cute #mirror #mirrortrick #trick #reflection #PhotoArk #15YearsofPhotoArk

node.text: 15 Years of Photo Ark Celebration/ This mother and baby white-bellied pangolin are part of @pangolinconservation, a non-profit organization in Florida. In the wild, this species is found in West and Central Africa, but the biggest threat to their survival comes from an entirely different continent - Asia. All eight species of pangolin are in danger of extinction due to the illegal trafficking of both live pangolins and the body parts of deceased individuals - especially their scales, which are used in Asia as traditional medicine because of the false belief that the scales contain curative properties. Many governmental groups and NGOs are working hard to combat the trafficking crisis, but they need your help. Use the power of your network to share this incredible species with as many people as you can and bring attention to the threats they are facing. #pangolin #pup #momandbaby #baby #mom #scales #whitebellied #vulnerable #PhotoArk #15YearsofPhotoArk

node.text: 15 Years of Photo Ark Celebration/ For years, nobody knew what this mysterious wild cat species, the guiña, sounded like. Today we do! Thanks to @fauna_andina, a conservation and research center in central-south Chile, we can share the sounds of this cat for the very first time. Hand-raised by the center after arriving as a ten-day-old orphan, today his vocalizations announce he is one happy cat; those low, fast-repeating sounds you hear are made when he’s excited, while the meow announces his presence. Over the past 15 years, the staff at Fauna Andina has been studying this cryptic cat and was the first to record their vocalizations, as well as breed them. They have also released several of these rare felines back into the wilds of central Chile, giving hope for the future of the species. Fauna Andina’s conservation work with other Andean wildlife continues today, with the center not only rescuing, rehabilitating and releasing guiñas back to the wild, but saving other rare Andean animals as well, including native deer like the pudu and the huemul, both rare species. #cat #guina #male #happy #excited #rare #InternationalCatDay #PhotoArk #15YearsofPhotoArk

node.text: 15 Years of Photo Ark Celebration/ Koalas rely on eucalyptus trees for food, shelter and safety against predators. As housing developments and busy roads encroach into koala habitat and decrease the number of available eucalyptus trees, they’re left vulnerable to being hit by traffic, dog attacks, and the spread of life-threatening diseases like chlamydia. The Australia Zoo Wildlife Hospital (@wildlifewarriorsworldwide), where this photograph was taken, provides care for up to 800 sick and injured koalas each year, making it Australia’s busiest koala hospital. Their tireless efforts give koalas like Augustine and her young ones Gus and Rupert a second chance at life in the wild. #koala #mom #baby #trio #babies #joeys #marsupial #Augustine #Gus #Rupert #PhotoArk #15YearsofPhotoArk

node.text: 15 Years of Photo Ark Celebration/ If a competition for the cutest rodent existed, the four-toed jerboa would surely become a top contender. Found in the dry deserts of Egypt and Libya, this species relies on its oversized ears to help regulate its body temperature and detect the insects it needs for food. Jerboas are also well known for their ability to avoid predators by leaping in a zig-zag pattern, often covering distances of up to three meters in a single jump.
